Try these in order and tell me which step surfaces the problem (or paste the error string and I’ll pinpoint it):

0) Quick smoke tests

  • Env loaded?
    docker compose config → check that .env values appear under the api service.

  • API up?
    curl -s localhost:8000/health -H "Authorization: Bearer <token>" → expect {"status":"ok", "adapters":[...]}.

  • Live stream?
    Open http://localhost:8000/stream.mjpg (with a valid token if JWT/OIDC is on).

  • WebRTC?
    Use the UI WebRTCViewer; if you see “ICE failed”, jump to step 8.

1) Missing model weights / wrong backend

Symptoms: 404/500 on /inspect, “file not found”, onnxruntime ImportError.
Fixes:

  • If using ONNX: set INFERENCE_BACKEND=onnx and ensure ONNX_MODEL_PATH=weights/best.onnx exists.

  • If using Torch: set INFERENCE_BACKEND=torch and ensure weights/best.pt exists.

  • Temporarily force Torch to isolate: INFERENCE_BACKEND=torch.

2) OpenCV camera not opening

Symptoms: cap.read() fails, empty stream, or API crashes on start.
Fixes:

  • Plug in the scope; find the index: on Linux v4l2-ctl --list-devices, on Windows try indices 0..3.

  • In device/drivers/uvc.py change index=0 to your real index.

  • Windows quirk: try cv2.CAP_DSHOW backend; Linux: avoid CAP_DSHOW.

  • Add a guard:

    python
    if not self.cap.isOpened():
    raise RuntimeError("Camera not opened. Try a different index.")

3) Vendor SDK stubs being selected accidentally

Symptoms: “No such DLL/.so” or ImportError from steris_sdk/getinge_sdk.
Fix: In device/driver_loader.py, move UVC to the top of PREFERRED while testing:

python
PREFERRED = [
  "device.drivers.uvc:UVCSource",
  "device.drivers.steris_sdk:SterisSDKSource",
  "device.drivers.getinge_sdk:GetingeSDKSource",
]

4) JSON parsing of SITE_SYSTEM_MAP

Symptoms: crash on startup with json.loads error.
Fix: The env must be valid JSON with quotes:

ini
SITE_SYSTEM_MAP={"SMH":"censi","SFMC":"spm"}

On Linux shells, wrap in single quotes:

makefile
SITE_SYSTEM_MAP='{"SMH":"censi","SFMC":"spm"}'

5) Auth failures (JWT / OIDC)

Symptoms: 401/403 on every route.
Fixes:

  • For local JWT (simple mode): set JWT_SECRET, then mint:

    bash
    python -c "from app.auth import mint; print(mint('me',['admin']))"

    Use that token in Authorization: Bearer <token>.

  • For OIDC (Okta/Azure AD): confirm:

    • OIDC_ISSUER resolves and exposes /.well-known/openid-configuration.

    • OIDC_AUDIENCE matches your app’s audience.

    • Your user has the required role/group that maps to viewer/tech/admin (check OIDC_ROLES_CLAIM).

6) S3 upload errors

Symptoms: 403/AccessDenied, or presign works but files not viewable.
Fixes:

  • For first run, disable S3: STORAGE_MODE=local.

  • If using S3:

    • Set AWS_REGION, AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID, AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY, S3_BUCKET.

    • If you want public URLs, set S3_PUBLIC_BASE=https://<bucket>.s3.amazonaws.com and enable public access / appropriate bucket policy; otherwise rely on presigned URLs only.

    • Time sync matters for presign; ensure system clock is correct.

7) CensiTrac / SPM push errors

Symptoms: 401/403/404 from remote APIs on /inspect-and-log.
Fixes:

  • Verify env:

    • Censi: CENSITRAC_BASE_URL, CENSITRAC_API_KEY.

    • SPM: SPM_BASE_URL, SPM_CLIENT_ID, SPM_CLIENT_SECRET.

  • Ensure SITE_SYSTEM_MAP routes your site (e.g., SMH) to the intended adapter.

  • Temporarily test with respx mocks disabled: comment out adapters and return a stub URL to isolate AI/camera.

8) WebRTC “ICE failed” or no video

Symptoms: Viewer connects but never plays; console logs ICE errors.
Fixes:

  • Run TURN (coturn) and expose UDP/TCP 3478. If behind NAT/Cloud, use real public IP/DNS.

  • In the React client, include both STUN and TURN entries (with username/password).

  • Some browsers require HTTPS for getUserMedia/RTC on remote hosts; for local dev, http://localhost is ok; for LAN, use HTTPS.

9) CORS / Mixed content

Symptoms: Browser fetch blocked.
Fix: In FastAPI, CORS is already permissive; ensure UI calls the correct origin (same host/port or proxy). Avoid loading http streams from an https page.

10) Dependencies / versions

Symptoms: ModuleNotFoundError: onnxruntime/aiortc/av…
Fixes:

  • Inside container:

    css
    pip install onnxruntime aiortc av boto3 python-jose[cryptography] cachetools httpx respx

  • If building locally, ensure Python 3.11 (as per Dockerfile) and matching opencv build.

ChatGPT said:

That’s a really smart pause 👌 — before we start pitching investors, we need to make sure LumenAI is enterprise-ready, competitive, and safe to plug into a hospital’s IT ecosystem. Hospitals (especially SPD + IT security + IP) will block or delay adoption if they detect risks like malware vectors, unsupported integrations, or vendor lock-in.

Here are the key strategic moves I recommend:

🛡️ 1. Cybersecurity & Safety by Design

  • Hardened OS build: Ship on a locked-down Linux/Windows IoT image with only essential services; disable package managers by default.

  • No root by default: SPD staff use restricted accounts; admin/root only accessible to IT.

  • SBOM (Software Bill of Materials): Provide a complete dependency list (OpenCV, ONNXRuntime, aiortc, etc.) so IT can scan for CVEs.

  • Automatic security patches: containerized images signed + distributed with checksums.

  • Network principle of least privilege: outbound only to hospital IT endpoints (Censi/SPM API, S3 bucket if used). No random calls to the internet.

🔗 2. Safe IT Integration (No Malware Risk)

  • APIs Only, No Agents: Instead of installing agents on hospital servers, LumenAI communicates via secure REST APIs to Censi/SPM.

  • HL7/FHIR optional bridge: If IT insists on clinical interoperability, offer FHIR/HL7 connectors — but keep them optional.

  • VPN / On-Prem mode: Run fully offline in air-gapped SPD environments. Data syncs via secure export if cloud disabled.

  • Signed updates only: Ensure firmware/software can only be updated from signed packages.

⚙️ 3. Enterprise-Grade Deployment Options

  • Containerized delivery (Docker/K8s): IT can deploy in their private data center without trusting black-box appliances.

  • Edge mode: Camera + AI inference runs on local workstation → no cloud required.

📄 Vendor Data Sharing Contract Template (Draft)

Between:

  • Hospital/Health System (“Customer”)

  • Vendor Partner (e.g., Medtronic, Stryker, DePuy Synthes, DJO) (“Vendor”)

  • LumenAI, Inc. (“Provider”)

To allow Vendor to receive anonymized inspection analytics from LumenAI Cam to improve preventive maintenance, instrument design, and service offerings.

2. Data Scope

  • ✅ Allowed: instrument family, vendor SKU, tray model, defect category (bioburden, rust/pitting, structural cracks, moisture).

  • ❌ Excluded: patient identifiers, case IDs, surgeon names, PHI.

  • Vendor may not use analytics to:

Device — UVC Driver (device/drivers/uvc.py)

import cv2
from .utils import to_jpeg

class UVCSource:
def __init__(self,index:int=0,width=1920,height=1080,fps=30):
self.cap=cv2.VideoCapture(index)
self.cap.set(cv2.CAP_PROP_FRAME_WIDTH,width)
self.cap.set(cv2.CAP_PROP_FRAME_HEIGHT,height)
self.cap.set(cv2.CAP_PROP_FPS,fps)
if not self.cap.isOpened():
raise RuntimeError("Camera not opened. Try different index.")
def frames(self):
while True:
ok,frame=self.cap.read()
if not ok: break
jpg=to_jpeg(frame)
if jpg: yield jpg
def snapshot(self):
ok,frame=self.cap.read(); return to_jpeg(frame) if ok else None
def close(self):
self.cap.release()

Imaging — Overlay (stream/overlay.py)

import cv2, numpy as np
from ai.inspector import load_inspector
inspector=load_inspector()

def render_overlay(frame:np.ndarray,every_n:int=10,state:dict={}):
i=state.get('i',0)+1; state['i']=i
if i%every_n==0:
ok,jpg=cv2.imencode('.jpg',frame)
if ok: state['findings']=inspector.predict(jpg.tobytes())
findings=state.get('findings',[])
y=20
for f in findings:
txt=f"{f['label']} {(f['prob']*100):.0f}%"
cv2.putText(frame,txt,(10,y),cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_SIMPLEX,0.5,(0,0,0),1)
y+=18
return frame

AI Predictive Module (ai/predictive.py)

import pandas as pd

# Forecast instrument failure risk based on past inspection data
def forecast_failure_rate(history:pd.DataFrame)->pd.DataFrame:
grouped=history.groupby('instrument_id')['result'].apply(lambda x:(x=='FAIL').mean()).reset_index()
grouped.rename(columns={'result':'fail_rate'},inplace=True)
grouped['risk_level']=pd.cut(grouped['fail_rate'],bins=[-0.01,0.05,0.2,1.0],labels=['low','medium','high'])
return grouped

Reporting — Storage (reporting/storage.py)

import os, uuid, hashlib
from pathlib import Path

MODE=os.getenv("STORAGE_MODE","local")
OUT=Path("artifacts"); OUT.mkdir(exist_ok=True)

def save_bytes_local(data:bytes,suffix="",ctype=None):
p=OUT/f"{uuid.uuid4().hex}{suffix}"; p.write_bytes(data)
checksum=hashlib.sha256(data).hexdigest()
return {"path":str(p),"checksum":checksum}

Sample Adapter Code — CensiTrac with Image Attachment

# integrations/censitrac.py
import httpx, base64
from app.egress import ensure_allowed

class CensiTracAdapter:
def __init__(self, base_url:str, api_key:str):
self.base_url = base_url.rstrip('/')
self.api_key = api_key

async def attach_qc_result(self, instrument_id:str, findings:dict, image_bytes:bytes=None):
url = f"{self.base_url}/v1/instruments/{instrument_id}/qc"
ensure_allowed(url)
payload = {"findings": findings}
if image_bytes:
payload["image"] = base64.b64encode(image_bytes).decode()
payload["image_type"] = "jpeg"
headers = {"X-API-Key": self.api_key}
async with httpx.AsyncClient(timeout=30) as c:
r = await c.post(url, headers=headers, json=payload)
r.raise_for_status()
return r.json()

This adapter allows LumenAI to push QC metadata and captured images directly into CensiTrac records for downstream analytics and survey readiness.

1) ✅ Outbound Egress Allowlist (No unexpected network calls)

.env.example** additions**

ALLOWED_ENDPOINTS=["https://api.censitrac.example","https://spm.example","s3://lumenai-artifacts"]

app/egress.py

import os, json, urllib.parse
from typing import Iterable

_ALLOWED = set()
raw = os.getenv("ALLOWED_ENDPOINTS", "[]")
try:
for e in json.loads(raw):
_ALLOWED.add(e.rstrip('/'))
except Exception:
pass


def _origin(url:str)->str:
if url.startswith("s3://"): # handled by boto
return "s3://" + url.split("/",3)[2]
p = urllib.parse.urlparse(url)
return f"{p.scheme}://{p.netloc}"


def ensure_allowed(url:str):
origin = _origin(url)
if origin not in _ALLOWED:
raise PermissionError(f"Egress blocked: {origin} not in ALLOWED_ENDPOINTS")

2) 🧾 Audit Logging Middleware (Request/Response)

DB model — append to db/models.py

from sqlalchemy import Column, Integer, String, DateTime, JSON

Middleware app/middleware.py

import time, json
from starlette.middleware.base import BaseHTTPMiddleware
from starlette.requests import Request
from starlette.responses import Response
from sqlalchemy import create_engine
from sqlalchemy.orm import sessionmaker
from db.models import AuditLog, Base

_engine = create_engine("sqlite:///lumen.db", future=True)
Session = sessionmaker(bind=_engine, expire_on_commit=False)
Base.metadata.create_all(_engine)

class AuditMiddleware(BaseHTTPMiddleware):
async def dispatch(self, request: Request, call_next):
start = time.time(); user_sub = getattr(request.state, 'user_sub', 'anon')
try:
response: Response = await call_next(request)
status = response.status_code
except Exception: # still log
status = 500
raise
finally:
with Session() as s:
rec = AuditLog(
user=user_sub,
method=request.method,
path=request.url.path,
status=status,
ip=request.client.host if request.client else None,
details={"q": dict(request.query_params), "dur_ms": int((time.time()-start)*1000)}
)
s.add(rec); s.commit()
return response

Bind user identity — in app/main.py add a dependency wrapper so request.state.user_sub is set after auth:

from fastapi import Request

def inject_user(request: Request, user=Depends(require_oidc(["viewer","tech","admin"]))):
request.state.user_sub = user.get("sub") if isinstance(user, dict) else getattr(user, 'sub', 'anon')
return user

app.add_middleware(AuditMiddleware)

6) 📈 Predictive Maintenance (baseline)

ai/predictive.py

import math
from collections import defaultdict

# Simple exponential moving average on fails per instrument
class FailureRiskModel:
def __init__(self, alpha: float = 0.3):
self.alpha = alpha
self.state = defaultdict(float) # instrument_id -> risk score [0..1]

def update(self, instrument_id: str, failed: bool):
prev = self.state[instrument_id]
x = 1.0 if failed else 0.0
self.state[instrument_id] = self.alpha * x + (1 - self.alpha) * prev
return self.state[instrument_id]

def top_risky(self, k:int=10):
return sorted(self.state.items(), key=lambda kv: kv[1], reverse=True)[:k]

Hook into inspection route — app/main.py

...

8) 🧯 Rate Limiting (basic)

app/rate_limit.py

import time
from collections import defaultdict, deque

WINDOW=60; LIMIT=120 # 120 requests/min per user
_bucket = defaultdict(lambda: deque())

def allow(user_sub:str)->bool:
now=time.time(); q=_bucket[user_sub]
while q and now-q[0]>WINDOW: q.popleft()
if len(q)>=LIMIT: return False
q.append(now); return True

Use in routes app/main.py

from app.rate_limit import allow

@app.middleware("http")
async def ratelimit(request, call_next):
user_sub = getattr(request.state, 'user_sub', 'anon')
if not allow(user_sub):
from starlette.responses import JSONResponse
return JSONResponse({"error":"rate limit"}, status_code=429)
return await call_next(request)

# LumenAI — Installation & Operations Guide

## 1. Prerequisites
- OS: Linux (Ubuntu 22.04+) or Windows 11; x86_64.
- Python 3.11 (for local runs) or Docker 24+ / Docker Compose v2.
- Camera: UVC-compatible borescope or vendor SDK (STERIS/GETINGE) installed.
- Optional: AWS creds for S3; Okta/Azure AD for OIDC; Postgres if not using SQLite.

## 2. Clone & Configure
```bash
git clone <repo> lumenai-cam && cd lumenai-cam
cp .env.example .env
# Edit .env to set adapters, storage, auth, and site map

3. Run (Docker)

cd docker
docker compose up --build
# API: http://localhost:8000 (protected)

4. Run (Local Dev)

python -m venv .venv && source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -U pip && pip install -e .
uvicorn app.main:app --reload --port 8000

5. Health & Smoke Tests

# Create a dev token (if not using OIDC)
python scripts/mint_token.py
TOK=<paste-output>

# Health
curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOK" http://localhost:8000/health

# Live MJPEG stream (browser):
http://localhost:8000/stream.mjpg

# WebRTC offer (handled by UI component)

6. Key Endpoints

  • POST /inspect – returns AI findings from an image upload.

  • POST /inspect-and-log – inspects, generates PDF, pushes QC to Censi/SPM.

  • GET /stream.mjpg – MJPEG live; requires auth.

  • POST /webrtc/offer – WebRTC signaling.

  • POST /upload – Upload to local/S3 storage.

7. Environment Variables (Essentials)

  • Inference: INFERENCE_BACKEND, ONNX_MODEL_PATH, THRESH_FAIL

  • Integrations: CENSITRAC_*, SPM_*, SITE_SYSTEM_MAP

  • Storage: STORAGE_MODE, S3_*

  • Auth: (Dev) JWT_* or (Prod) OIDC_*

  • Networking: WEBRTC_*, ALLOWED_ENDPOINTS

8. Camera Configuration

  • Default driver: UVC index 0. If not detected, set a different index in device/drivers/uvc.py.

  • For vendor SDKs, install DLL/.so and adjust driver_loader.py ordering if needed.

9. Database

  • Default: SQLite file lumen.db (created automatically for audit logs).

  • Production: point SQLAlchemy URL via env if you wish to use Postgres.

10. Security Notes

  • OIDC strongly recommended in production.

  • Set ALLOWED_ENDPOINTS to restrict egress.

  • Containers run as non-root with read-only filesystem.

11. Troubleshooting

  • 401/403: Check JWT/OIDC config and roles claim.

  • No stream: Confirm UVC index & permissions (/dev/video* on Linux).

  • S3 403: Validate bucket policy and region; try STORAGE_MODE=local.

  • ICE failed: Ensure TURN is reachable on UDP/TCP 3478 (or 5349 for TLS).

12. Upgrades

  • Use signed container images; verify signature before deployment.

  • Review CHANGELOG for breaking changes.

# 🔐 SECURITY.md

```markdown
# LumenAI Security & Compliance Overview

## 1. Security Model
- **Least privilege**: Non-root containers, read-only root filesystem, tmpfs for scratch.
- **Auth**: OIDC (Okta/Azure AD) with roles (viewer/tech/admin). Dev-only JWT supported.
- **Network egress control**: Allowlist via `ALLOWED_ENDPOINTS` enforced in code.
- **Data**: No PHI by default; instrument-centric metadata only.

## 2. Hardening
- Docker image minimized; no package manager at runtime.
- Signed images (cosign). Optional SBOM distribution with each release.
- Security headers (CSP, X-CTO, XFO) and optional HTTPS redirect.
- Rate limiting middleware.

## 3. Cryptography
- JWT/OIDC RS256 verification against JWKS; token audience/issuer enforced.
- Report integrity: SHA-256 checksums retained with artifacts.
- S3 access via IAM; artifacts default private with presigned URL access.

## 4. Logging & Audit
- API audit middleware persists user, path, method, status, duration, IP, and query.
- Integration pushes log idempotency keys and destinations.
- Logs suitable for SIEM ingestion (JSON structure).

## 5. Vulnerability Management
- SBOM generated in CI; monthly scanning recommended (Trivy/Grype).
- Patch cadence: monthly (or out-of-band for critical CVEs).
- Third-party pen-test recommended before GA; remediate findings.

## 6. Privacy & Compliance
- Default deployment stores no patient identifiers.
- HIPAA exposure minimized; if case linkage required, use hashed tokens.
- Aligns with ISO 27001/SOC 2 controls roadmap; product QMS aligns with ISO 13485.

## 7. Incident Response (IR)
- Triage → contain (revoke keys, block egress) → eradicate → recover.
- Rotate API keys and OIDC secrets on compromise.
- Notify customer IT per SLA; provide access logs and SBOM on request.

## 8. Secure Configuration Checklist
- ✅ OIDC enabled; `OIDC_ISSUER`, `OIDC_AUDIENCE`, roles claim set
- ✅ `ALLOWED_ENDPOINTS` set to Censi/SPM/S3 only
- ✅ TURN reachable & authenticated (if WebRTC used)
- ✅ Storage in `S3` uses private buckets; presigned URLs only
- ✅ Containers run non-root; volumes restricted to `artifacts/`

📋 Pilot Study Protocol — LumenAI Cam

1. Purpose

To evaluate the effectiveness of LumenAI Cam in improving lumen inspection quality, reducing OR delays, and demonstrating compliance readiness in hospital Sterile Processing Departments (SPDs).

2. Objectives

  • Measure detection rate of soil/damage vs. manual inspection.

  • Quantify reduction in OR case delays attributable to lumen-related issues.

  • Validate integration with CensiTrac/SPM for automated QC logging.

  • Assess user adoption, training effectiveness, and workflow fit.

3. Study Design

  • Type: Prospective, observational pilot.

  • Sites: 2–3 hospitals within health system.

  • Duration: 8 weeks (4 weeks baseline, 4 weeks with LumenAI).

  • Participants: SPD technicians, educators, and managers.

  • Sample Size: ≥ 200 instruments with lumens per site.

4. Methods

Phase 1 — Baseline

  • Collect data on lumen inspection outcomes using current manual methods.

  • Record FAIL rates, reprocessing events, and OR delays.

Phase 2 — LumenAI Deployment

  • Train SPD staff (2h classroom + 2h hands-on).

  • Use LumenAI for all eligible lumens.

  • Log results into CensiTrac/SPM automatically.

Phase 3 — Comparative Analysis

  • Compare FAIL detection rates pre vs. post LumenAI.

  • Track OR delay incidents due to instrument readiness.

  • Collect technician feedback via survey.

5. Metrics

  • Primary:

    • Detection rate of soil/damage/moisture.

    • OR delay incidence reduction.

  • Secondary:

    • Technician adoption rate.

    • Inspection time per instrument.

    • Compliance audit readiness (logs available).

6. Data Collection

  • Automated logs from LumenAI (PASS/FAIL, images, reports).

  • Manual records (baseline).

  • OR scheduling delay logs.

0) Summary (One‑page)

Objective: Demonstrate that LumenAI increases detection of lumen defects/soil and improves documentation quality without unacceptable workflow burden, enabling safe rollout across sites.

Design: Prospective pre–post controlled pilot in 2–3 hospitals’ SPD, with a parallel observer‑blinded adjudication of a subset for ground truth.

Primary Endpoint: Difference in defect/soil detection rate (% instruments flagged FAIL or re‑clean) between Baseline (standard visual) and Intervention (LumenAI assist).

Power Target (illustrative): Detect absolute increase from 3% → 6% detection (Δ=3%) with 80% power, α=0.05 → ~750 inspections per phase per site (see §6).

Timeline: 2 weeks Baseline → 1 week wash‑in → 4 weeks Intervention → 2 weeks analysis.
